snippet.textDisplay: I've got a few things to say: first of all, you are BEAUTIFUL no matter what. Secondly, I understand what you said about the social aspect of it, and that's a really difficult commitment. I've been a vegetarian since birth so I am very used to it and also it's far easier than veganism, and I understand especially if you're switching from a meat-eating diet, there are a lot of changes in your life. However, at least from this video you seem to be doing a lot better not just for things like skin and hair, but also emotionally, so what I recommend, if you don't want to become fully vegan/vegetarian, is have 1 week a month where you are vegan (and this can increase gradually if you get more comfortable with it). I think this way you can continue eating meat but also feel close to how you've felt with this challenge. I do have friends who do this and it works really well for them! It's your choice in the end though, but remember, no matter what, you are beautiful inside and out.

snippet.textDisplay:
Seeing Morgan happy about herself is like, a goddamn blessing, holy shit.

BUT, You really should listen if a doctor sais you're lactose intolerant. Some of us are a lot more sensetive than others, and it does affect everything from your mood, to skin, to physical comfotability.
I've known about my lactose and gluten-intolerances for about 6 years now, and I can't describe it in any other way than- Instead of being sick all the time, (Literally every single day except for a few seconds in-between) I'm now normal.
My whole world opened up, and my life changed radically forever, just becuase I stopped eating things that my body couldn't really take care of. I didn't even know I was actually getting sick from certain foods, and to this day, I still can't believe I was so sick for so long, and how I feel now is what's normal. (I had no doctor to speak of, so I had to figure it out from testing what I could eat) But it's important to try your body out, get to know it. Everyone works differently.

It's not about weight either, not at all. It's about what your internal organs can actually handle, and process. ( It is however extremely easier to lose weight when you don't eat things that your body literally can't process.)
